\begin_layout Standard
The continued maintenance of diversity in spite of widespread competition
 has long bewildered ecologists, especially for primary producers such as
 phytoplankton that share the same basic resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hutchinson_paradox_1961"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A solution for the `paradox of the plankon' was proposed by Hutchinson:
 temporal variation of the environment.
 By making the identity of the fittest species change over time, temporal
 variation could render competitive exclusion less likely, which was confirmed
 by early experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sommer_paradox_1984"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, it has been shown later that inclusion of temporal variability
 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
 in competition models is not sufficient for maintaining a realistic diversity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_roles_1997,fox_intermediate_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additional mechanisms such as the storage effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_multispecies_1994,ellner_how_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or a relative nonlinearity of competition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "armstrong_r.a._competitive_1980,chesson_mechanisms_2000,descamps-julien_stable_2005,jiang_temperature_2007,fox_intermediate_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 need to be introduced for diversity to maintain.
 Moreover, richness rarely exceeds a handful to a dozen of species in model
 competitive communities in fluctuating environments, except when external
 inputs from immigration sustain diversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g., "
key "huisman_towards_2001,jabot_non-random_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To our knowledge, the effect of temporal variability on persistence in
 competition models has mostly been examined in theoretical communities
 of 2 to 3 species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "chesson_roles_1997,litchman_competition_2001,li_effects_2016,miller_evolutionary_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the richest modeled communities that we identified can be found in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which is based on temperature variation and different thermal optima for
 each species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moisan_modelling_2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this model, the synchronizing effect of the environment and the storage
 effect can maintain 12 phytoplankton-like species on average.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described daily temperature as a random noise, i.e., independent and identically
 distributed Gaussian random variates over time.
 However, under most latitudes, seasonality drives part of the environmental
 variation: over short timescales, random temporal variations often only
 add noise to a largely deterministic seasonal trend 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scheffer_seasonal_1997,boyce_environmental_2017,barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seasonal forcing of parameters can strongly affect the dynamics of model
 communities by synchronizing species to the seasonal signal or even promoting
 oscillations with lower frequency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rinaldi_multiple_1993,barabas_community_2012,miller_evolutionary_2017,vesipa_impact_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 How seasonality affects coexistence, as opposed to a randomly fluctuating
 environment, is therefore a key feature of this paper.
 Our present work can be seen as an attempt to blend 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

's stochastic framework with the periodic environments of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barabas_community_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, to better represent the mixture of stochastic and deterministic environmental
 forces affecting phytoplankton community dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What other key features of field communities should be considered when modeling
 phytoplankton? Strong self-regulation, with intraspecific competition much
 stronger than interspecific interactions, has been found to be widespread
 in terrestrial plant communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_competition_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, animal communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mutshinda_what_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and phytoplanktonic communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We will therefore insert those niche differences, manifesting as strong
 self-regulation, into our models of phytoplankton competition.
 The interaction between environment variability and niche overlap was investiga
ted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abrams_niche_1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but his results did not extend to communities more diverse than 4 species;
 our objective is therefore to see how those mechanisms interact for species-ric
h communities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Niche models have often been opposed to the neutral theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hubbell_unified_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where dispersal and drift can ensure a transient coexistence of many species,
 but several authors have attempted to blend niche and neutral processes
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gravel_reconciling_2006,scheffer_self-organized_2006,carmel_using_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 An intriguing offshoot of these attempts is the concept of `clumpy coexistence'
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scheffer_self-organized_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, whereby simultaneous influences of both niche and neutral processes create
 several clumps of similar species along a single trait axis.
 Niche differences enable coexistence of multiple clumps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_mechanisms_2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 while within-clump coexistence occurs through neutral processes.
 This `emergent neutrality' within groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holt_emergent_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has been proposed as a unifying concept for niche and neutral theories
 (even though the neutrality of the original model has been disputed due
 to hidden niches, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Since then, clumpy coexistence has been shown to occur in theoretical models
 incorporating a temporally variable environment interacting with a thermal
 preference trait axis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scranton_coexistence_2016,sakavara_lumpy_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The relationship (or absence thereof) between biomass-trait distributions
 and coexistence mechanisms is currently debated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dandrea_challenges_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, although there are suggestions that clustering on trait axes under competition
 may be a robust find 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dandrea_translucent_2018,dandrea_generalizing_2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we try to establish what are the relative contributions to coexistence
 of the storage effect vs strong self-regulation, in a phytoplankton-like
 theoretical community model with a large number of species.
 This led us to cross combinations of seasonality vs randomness in the forcing
 signal, presence of the storage effect or not, and intra- vs interspecific
 competition intensity, in order to disentangle the contributions of these
 factors to biodiversity maintenance and their potential interactions.
 Alongside the resulting species richness, we also report which biomass-trait
 distribution can be expected under a given combination of processes leading
 to coexistence.
\end_layout

