\begin_layout Standard
The original environmental forcing is a normally distributed variable centered
 on 293 K (20°C), with a 5 K dispersion.
 Temperature varies from one day to the next, but is kept constant throughout
 the day.
 At and above the daily scale, temperature could therefore be considered
 as a white noise 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vasseur_color_2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, from a mathematical viewpoint, the noise is slightly autocorrelated
 as the integration process goes below the daily time step.
 We therefore use the expression `random noise' to describe this forcing,
 as opposed to the `seasonal noise' described hereafter.
 To construct the seasonal noise, we add to the random forcing signal a
 lower-frequency component, using a sinusoidal function with a period of
 365 days (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Seasonal_signal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 We tune the ratio of low-to-high frequency with the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 so as to keep the same energy content - i.e., equal total variance - in the
 forcing signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau(t)=\mu_{\tau}+\theta\sigma_{\tau}\sin\left(2\pi t\right)+\epsilon_{t},\text{where }\epsilon_{t}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,\sigma_{\tau}\sqrt{1-\frac{\theta^{2}}{2}}\right)\label{eq:Seasonal_signal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the upper limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, corresponds to a completely deterministic model which we do not explore
 here (but see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zhao1991qualitative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proving bounded coexistence).
 We choose to keep the stochasticity in the signal and to model a plausible
 temperature signal with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1.3$
\end_inset

 (illustrated in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Times-series_temperature_species"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b) when considering a seasonal forcing of the dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulation of the forced Lotka-Volterra model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 implies a storage effect, as the net effect of competition exerted by species
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is the product of the temperature-related growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and the competitive strength 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

 exerted by species 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 multiplied by its abundance 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, total net competition (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{S}r_{i}(\tau)\alpha_{ij}N_{j}$
\end_inset

) covaries positively with the growth rate values 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, which defines the storage effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_multispecies_1994,fox_intermediate_2013,ellner_how_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To remove the assumption of an explicit storage effect, we create another
 version of the model using the mean value of a species' growth rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

) to weight the interaction coefficients (see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eqLV_noforcecompetition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The mean growth rate value is computed by first generating the temperature
 time series and then averaging all 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 over the corresponding sequences of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dN_{i}}{dt}=N_{i}\left(r_{i}(\tau)-\sum_{j=1}^{S}\bar{r}_{i}\alpha_{ij}N_{j}\right)-mN_{i}\label{eq:eqLV_noforcecompetition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eqLV_noforcecompetition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, net competition remains unaffected by the environmental conditions, in
 contrast to intrinsic growth rates, while preserving the same average magnitude
 of competition as in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:modelLV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strong self-regulation is ensured by the addition of the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, which is the ratio of intra-to-interspecific competition strength.
 We can therefore re-write the interaction coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:alpha_def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{ij}=\alpha\left(1+(\kappa-1)\delta_{ij}\right)\label{eq:alpha_def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker symbol, equal to 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

 and to 0 otherwise.
 The value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=10$
\end_inset

 was chosen from analyses of phytoplanktonic data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hereafter, the expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

strong self-regulation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 characterizes dynamics where the intraspecific competition strength is
 10 times higher than the interspecific competition strength, as opposed
 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equal competitive strengths
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where intra- and interspecific competition strengths are equal.
\end_layout

